# Introducing the SmolNet (The Small Internet), and Why You Should Use It

The SmolNet is a small section of internet technology and servers, built on an alternate set of protocols instead of the World-Wide Web's HTTP(S) and HTML. Rather than being advanced, complex protocols that make virtually anything possible, these protocols are explicitly designed to *limit* what is possible.

At first blush, that might sound like a very backwards attitude toward technology. But in this era where we are increasingly forced to confront that, ironically, the nearly-unlimited capabilities of the Web are increasingly being used to *limit* the capabilities, privacy, and freedom of *users*, suddenly limitations on the technology may not sound like such a bad idea.

When technology provides corporations and their platforms with the power to oppress and restrict users, it follows that building limitation into technology serves to *remove* limitations from the users!

The small internet, or "SmolNet", is not (only) small in that it has relatively few users—it's small in that it deliberately uses "small", uncomplicated protocols and technologies, with deliberately limited opportunity for extension or evolution. These protocols help to ensure that SmolNet will always remain small, and that you can therefore depend on it continuing to provide its unique protections on your privacy, your freedom, your distraction-free focus on actual content—and perhaps, your mental health, as a result.

# No Need to Abandon the Web!

But look. For all its flaws, the Web is vital, exciting, and incredibly, incredibly useful. There is a lot on the Web that I'm very, very excited and grateful about. There is a lot of joy that it brings to my life. No one is asking you to abandon the Web, least of all me.

Here are a handful of things that I am personally very enthusiastic about, and that are only possible because we kept pushing the Web to its limits.
=> https://jsnes.org/ I can play games on retro game consoles such as the NES
=> https://8bitworkshop.com/ I can write, compile, assemble, and debug my *own* NES (or other vintage console) game from scratch
=> https://www.beepbox.co/ I can compose, share, and export music
=> https://internet-janitor.itch.io/wigglypaint I can slap together wiggly animated doodles while taking a big hit of HyperCard nostalgia

I'm not going to stop using these amazing tools and resources, just because some *other* websites (or even maybe one or two of these) are giving me the icks!

But just because I'm not abandoning the web, doesn't mean I don't want to appreciate and participate in a community that's going in a different direction. The web has become so absolutely clogged with annoyances and hindrances, that it can feel a bit like I'm crawling on broken glass on my path from one Neat Thing to the next.

...Wouldn't it be nice to spend at least some of my time in a hall where glass hasn't even been invented/discovered? I can always go back to the glass-ridden-but-flashier halls I'll always be dependent on... but it's very nice to spend time in a place where I can "crawl" to my heart's content, with the supreme confidence of knowing I'll never encounter the tinyest shard there.

Read on to find out more about how the SmolNet saves you from the annoyances of the Web.

Or, if you're already chomping at the bit to get started,
=> /getting-started/ feel free to get started!
